### Proof of Corollary 9

Consider the following setup of linear bandits: let \(\theta^{\star}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\) be an unknown parameter. At time \(t\), the learner chooses an action \(\pi^{t}\in\left\{\pi\in\mathbb{R}^{d}:\left\|\pi\right\|_{2}\leq 1\right\}\) and receives a Gaussian reward \(r^{t}\sim\mathcal{N}(\left\langle\theta^{\star},\pi^{t}\right\rangle,1)\). For \(T\in\mathbb{N}\), let \(\mathcal{H}^{T}=(\pi^{1},r^{1},\cdots,\pi^{T},r^{T})\) be the observed history up to time \(T\). The central claim of this section is the following upper bound on the mutual information.

**Theorem D.3**.: _For any \(r>0\), we define the prior \(\mu_{r}\) over \(\mathbb{B}^{d}(r)\) by_

\[\mu_{r}:\theta^{\star}\sim\mathcal{N}\bigg{(}0,\frac{r^{2}}{4d}I_{d}\bigg{)} \mid\left\|\theta^{\star}\right\|\leq r.\]

_Then for any algorithm \(\mathsf{ALG}\), we have_

\[I_{\mu_{r},\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star};\mathcal{H}^{T})\leq d\log\bigg{(}1+ \frac{r^{2}T}{4d^{2}}\bigg{)}.\]

Proof.: Denote \(\lambda=\frac{r^{2}}{4}\). We first prove that if \(\theta^{\star}\sim\mu=\mathcal{N}(0,\lambda I_{d}/d)\), then

\[I_{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star};\mathcal{H}^{T})\leq\frac{d}{2}\log\bigg{(} 1+\frac{\lambda T}{d^{2}}\bigg{)}.\] (29)

By the Bayes rule, the posterior distribution of \(\theta^{\star}\) conditioned on \((\mathcal{H}^{t-1},\pi^{t})\) is

\[p(\theta^{\star}\mid\mathcal{H}^{t-1},\pi^{t})\propto\exp\Biggl{(}-\frac{d \|\theta^{\star}\|_{2}^{2}}{2\lambda}-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{s<t}(r^{s}-\langle\theta ^{\star},\pi^{s}\rangle)^{2}\Biggr{)},\]

which is a Gaussian distribution with covariance \((\Sigma^{t-1})^{-1}\), where

\[\Sigma^{t-1}=\frac{d}{\lambda}I_{d}+\sum_{s<t}\pi^{s}(\pi^{s})^{\top}.\]

Therefore, by the chain rule of mutual information, we have

\[I_{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star};\mathcal{H}^{T}) =\sum_{t=1}^{T}I_{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star};r^{t}\mid H^{t -1},\pi^{t})\] \[=\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mathbb{E}^{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}\bigg{[}\frac{1}{2} \log\bigl{(}1+(\pi^{t})^{\top}(\Sigma^{t-1})^{-1}\pi^{t}\bigr{)}\bigg{]}\] \[=\mathbb{E}^{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}\bigg{[}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{t=1}^{T} \log\frac{\det(\Sigma^{t})}{\det(\Sigma^{t-1})}\bigg{]}\] \[=\mathbb{E}^{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}\bigg{[}\frac{1}{2}\log\frac{\det( \Sigma^{T})}{(d/\lambda)^{d}}\bigg{]}\] \[\leq\mathbb{E}^{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}\bigg{[}\frac{d}{2}\log\frac{ \operatorname{Tr}(\Sigma^{T})/d}{d/\lambda}\bigg{]}\] \[\leq\frac{d}{2}\log\biggl{(}1+\frac{\lambda T}{d^{2}}\bigg{)},\]

which is exactly Eq. (29).

Next we deduce the claimed result from Eq. (29). Consider the random variable \(Z=\mathbf{1}\left\{\|\theta^{\star}\|_{2}\leq r\right\}\in\left\{0,1\right\}\), and then

\[\frac{d}{2}\log\left(1+\frac{\lambda T}{d^{2}}\right) \geq I_{\mu,\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star};\mathcal{H}^{T})\] \[\geq\mathbb{P}(Z=1)\cdot I_{\mu_{r},\mathsf{ALG}}(\theta^{\star}; \mathcal{H}^{T}|Z=1)\]\[=\mathbb{P}_{\mu}(\|\theta^{\star}\|_{2}\leq r)\cdot I_{\mu_{r},\mathbb{H}\mathbb{G} }(\theta^{\star};\mathcal{H}^{T}).\]

Here the first inequality is Eq. (29), the second inequality follows from \(I(X;Y)-I(X;Y\mid f(X))=I(f(X);Y)-I(f(X);Y\mid X)\geq 0\), the third identity follows from the definition of conditional mutual information. Finally, noticing that \(\mathbb{P}_{\mu}(\|\theta^{\star}\|_{2}\leq r)\geq\frac{1}{2}\) by concentration of \(\chi_{d}^{2}\) random variable, we arrive at the desired statement. 

