### Results for interactive estimation

More generally, we show that for a fairly different task of interactive estimation (Example 3), we also have an equivalence between quantile PAC-DEC with constrained PAC-DEC.

Recall that in this setting, each model \(M\in\mathcal{M}\) is assigned with a parameter \(\theta_{{}_{M}}\in\Theta\), which is the parameter that the agent want to estimate. The decision space \(\Pi=\Pi_{0}\times\Theta\), where each decision \(\pi\in\Pi\) consists of \(\pi=(\pi_{0},\theta)\), where \(\pi_{0}\) is the _explorative_ decision to interact with the model, and \(\theta\) is the estimator of the model parameter. The risk function is then defined as \(L(M,\pi)=\rho(\theta_{{}_{M}},\theta)\), for certain distance \(\rho(\cdot,\cdot)\).

In interactive estimation, we can show that the quantile DEC is in fact lower bounded the constrained DEC, as follows (proof in Appendix F.7).

**Proposition E.4**.: _Consider the setting of Example 3. Then as long as \(\delta<\frac{1}{2}\), it holds that_

\[\mathsf{p}\text{-}\mathsf{dec}^{\mathsf{c}}_{\varepsilon}(\mathcal{M})\leq 2 \cdot\mathsf{p}\text{-}\mathsf{dec}^{\mathsf{a}}_{\varepsilon,\delta}( \mathcal{M}).\]

In particular, for such a setting (which encompasses the model estimation task considered in Chen et al. [23]), Theorem 6 provides a lower bound of estimation error in terms of constrained PAC-DEC. This is significant because the constrained PAC-DEC upper bound in Theorem 4 is actually not restricted to Example 1, and we have hence shown that

\[\mathsf{p}\text{-}\mathsf{dec}^{\mathsf{c}}_{\underline{\varepsilon}(T)}( \mathcal{M})\lesssim\inf_{\mathcal{M}\in\mathcal{M}}\sup_{M^{\star}\in \mathcal{M}}\mathbb{E}^{\text{\tiny M}^{\star},\text{\tiny M}\in\mathcal{M}}[ \mathbf{Risk}_{\text{\tiny DM}}(T)]\lesssim\mathsf{p}\text{-}\mathsf{dec}^{ \mathsf{c}}_{\underline{\varepsilon}(T)}(\mathcal{M}),\]

where \(\underline{\varepsilon}(T)\asymp\sqrt{1/T}\) and \(\bar{\varepsilon}(T)\asymp\sqrt{\log|\mathcal{M}|/T}\). Therefore, for interactive estimation, constrained PAC-DEC is also a _nearly tight_ complexity measure.

**Remark E.5**.: The \(\log|\mathcal{M}|\)-gap between the lower and upper bound can further be closed for convex model class, utilizing the upper bounds in Appendix G.3. More specifically, we consider a convex model class \(\mathcal{M}\), where \(M\mapsto\theta_{{}_{M}}\) is a convex function on \(\mathcal{M}\). Then, a suitable instantiation of \(\mathsf{ExO}^{+}\) (Algorithm 1) achieves

\[\mathbf{Risk}_{\text{\tiny DM}}(T)\lesssim\Delta+\inf_{\gamma>0}\bigg{(}\mathsf{ p}\text{-}\mathsf{dec}^{\mathsf{o}}_{\gamma}(\mathcal{M})+\frac{\log N(\Theta, \Delta)+\log(1/\delta)}{T}\bigg{)},\]where \(N(\Theta,\Delta)\) is the \(\Delta\)-covering number of \(\Theta\), because we have \(\log\mathsf{N}_{\mathrm{frac}}(\mathcal{M},\Delta)\leq\log N(\Theta,\Delta)\) by considering the prior \(q=\mathrm{Unif}(\Theta_{0})\) for a minimal \(\Delta\)-covering of \(\Theta\). Similar to Theorem H.5, we can upper bound \(\mathsf{p}\mathsf{-dec}^{\mathsf{o}}_{\varepsilon}(\mathcal{M})\) by \(\mathsf{p}\mathsf{-dec}^{\mathsf{e}}_{\varepsilon}(\mathcal{M})\). Taking these pieces together, we can show that under the assumption that \(\mathsf{p}\mathsf{-dec}^{\mathsf{e}}_{\varepsilon}(\mathcal{M})\) is of moderate decay, \(\mathsf{ExO}^{+}\) achieves

\[\mathbf{Risk}_{\mathsf{DM}}(T)\lesssim\mathsf{p}\mathsf{-dec}^{\mathsf{c}}_{ \varepsilon(T)}(\mathcal{M}),\]

where \(\varepsilon(T)\asymp\sqrt{\log N(\Theta,1/T)/T}\).

In particular, for the (non-interactive) _functional estimation_ problem (see e.g. Polyanskiy and Wu [67]), the parameter space \(\Theta\subset\mathbb{R}\), and hence by considering covering number, we have \(\log|\Theta|=\tilde{O}\left(1\right)\). Therefore, for convex \(\mathcal{M}\), under mild assumption that the DEC is of moderate decaying (Assumption 3), the minimax risk is then characterized by (up to logarithmic factors)

\[\inf_{\mathsf{AL}\delta}\sup_{M^{\prime}\in\mathcal{M}}\mathbb{E}^{M^{\star},\mathsf{az}}[\mathbf{Risk}_{\mathsf{DM}}(T)]\asymp\mathsf{p}\mathsf{-dec}^{ \mathsf{c}}_{\sqrt{1/T}}(\mathcal{M}).\]

This result can be regarded as a generalization of Polyanskiy and Wu [67] to the interactive estimation setting.

